# Performance
1. GPU-side BVH traversal
You already serialized your three-mesh-bvh into buffers (bvhRootsBuffer, bvhIndexBuffer, bvhIndirectBuffer). Instead of a flat loop over all triangles, do a stack-based traversal of the BVH:
    1.	Load the root node’s AABB
	2.	Test sphere‐AABB (vertex ± threshold)
	3.	If it overlaps:
	    •	If it’s an internal node, push both children onto a small local stack.
	    •	If it’s a leaf, iterate only the few triangles in that leaf with your full distance test.
	4.	Early-exit once collisionFlag is set.

This converts an O(N) triangle scan into O(log N + k) where k is the tiny number of nearby triangles.

2. Precompute a Signed-Distance Field (SDF)
If your collider mesh is static, you can bake a 3D SDF texture (on the CPU) and then in the shader simply

3. Spatial Hash / Uniform Grid
Partition space into a coarse 3D grid (e.g. cell size = few × threshold). Precompute for each cell a short list of triangle indices. Upload that as a big “cell→triangle” buffer. Then in the shader:
	1.	Hash your point into a cell index.
	2.	Only loop the handful of triangles in that cell (and its 26 neighbors if you need to cover boundary cases).

This trades some memory for much less looping.

4. Workgroup-shared Culling
If you bind your cloth vertices in workgroups (e.g. 32 or 64 threads per WG), you can:
	•	Broadcast the same BVH traversal or grid-cell index among the group.
	•	Share the small stack or cell’s triangle list in workgroup-local memory.
This reduces redundant loads of the same BVH node or cell list.

5. Lower Cloth/Triangle Resolution
If you can tolerate it:
	•	Coarsen your cloth mesh (fewer vertices).
	•	Simplify the collider (decimate triangles where high fidelity isn’t needed).
	•	LODs: Use a very coarse mesh until the cloth gets extremely close.

7. Hardware-Accelerated Intersection (where available)
If your target supports WebGPU ray-query extensions or a dedicated raytracing pipeline, dispatch a GPU ray/point query against the BLAS of your mesh instead of custom compute shaders.










Debugging Plan
1. roots, index, indirectBuffer checken
	•	roots: an array of ArrayBuffers, each containing the top-level BVH node(s) serialized for GPU upload.
	•	index: a flat Float32Array of every node’s AABB (6 floats per node: minX, minY, minZ, maxX, maxY, maxZ).
	•	indirectBuffer: a typed array of child-pointer data (node offsets/indices) used for indirect, GPU-friendly BVH traversal.
